dBHVYsTef48.title: Making patterns with Numicon shapes
dBHVYsTef48.description:
Learning about numbers and maths can be fun! When a child makes patterns with Numicon apparatus they start to build number recognition by creating and describing patterns. As well as this, they will learn how to follow instructions and problem solve. 

The final step using the Numicon feeling bag allows the child to see the shape in their minds eye - this concept is important for learning maths later on in learning where it must be visualised in your head.  

Numicon is a primary school maths programme that offers parents and teachers a wealth of resources that can be used between the ages of 3-11 and bridging the gap to KS3.

For more information visit:
www.oxfordprimary.co.uk/numicon/

D7ku84LR2-8.title: What's next after Read Write Inc. Phonics?
D7ku84LR2-8.description:
Thinking about what’s next for your Year 2 children once they’ve finished Read Write Inc. Phonics? Rachel Green, Commissioning Editor at Oxford University Press, talks through two options in this 15 minute webinar: Read Write Inc. Comprehension and Read Write Inc. Spelling.
Developed by Ruth Miskin, both programmes are designed to continue to build upon and develop children’s literacy skills in fluency, comprehension and spelling. They use the same familiar teaching strategies as Read Write Inc. Phonics to maintain progress. 
You can also sign up for free modules from both programmes to try out at: http://bit.ly/38M4JNh

rxd-ERFK0yE.title: Numicon - maths in your hands
rxd-ERFK0yE.description:
Numicon is a primary school maths programme that offers teachers a wealth of resources that can be used between the ages of 4-11 and bridging the gap to KS3.

Based on a concrete-pictorial-abstract approach, Numicon encourages children to explore maths using structured imagery and apparatus in order to understand and explain mathematical concepts. Make the most of manipulatives or mastery by using Numicon resources.

Numicon:
- Can be used flexibly alongside your existing resources, or as a complete maths programme
- Includes a range of professional development options to suit the needs of your school and staff
- Helps you to assess a child’s understanding and progress by watching and listening to what they do and say
- Has been proven to have had a positive impact on children’s enjoyment as well as giving them the confidence to demonstrate how and why they arrived at their answer

For more information visit:
www.oxfordprimary.co.uk/numicon

Qeb_9IQs3Kk.title: Discover hispanic culture without leaving the KS3 Spanish classroom
Qeb_9IQs3Kk.description:
‘¡Claro! takes you places’ 
Watch this video to get a flavour of the hispanic culture your  students will discover when you use ¡Claro! KS3 Spanish in your classroom.

What are some of the festivals in Mexico? How do they celebrate Christmas is Spain? Who are the most famous celebrities that hispanic teenager follow?

With ¡Claro! KS3 Spanish your students will discover so much about traditions and festivals, sport, music and celebrities. Starting with the Student Book  which has culture spreads in each unit, ¡Claro! will take them on a journey from Spain to Mexico, Cuba, Peru and even Equitorial Guinea! The Student Book is supported Kerboodle which includes video in it’s bank of supporting interactive activities, worksheets and assessment and planning material. In the Kerboodle videos they’ll follow a group of teengagers in Bilbao and meet their friend Emiline in Guatemala who shares her country’s kite festival.

¡Claro! is a KS3 course that helps you captivate students’ interest and immerses them in the culture while they learn the language and build the right skills to progress to KS4 with confidence.

Get a free trial of ¡Claro! Kerboodle now email: secondary.enquiries@oup.com

kfEpy3doMKU.title: Cerrie Burnell reads The Girl with the Shark's Teeth
kfEpy3doMKU.description:
Children's author and former CBeebies presenter Cerrie Burnell reads from her debut middle grade story The Girl with the Shark's Teeth. 

Minnow feels an irresistible pull to water, and beneath the waves she feels free. When Minnow's mother is taken from her, she answers a call from the Wild Deep she has been waiting for her whole young life. In her brave and fearless mission, Minnow is transformed forever.

Find out more at https://www.amazon.co.uk/Girl-Sharks-Teeth-Cerrie-Burnell/dp/0192767542/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1549366721&sr=8-1&keywords=girl+with+the+shark%27s+teeth&_encoding=UTF8&tag=other-online-ads-21&linkCode=ur2&linkId=df3966df8cdfb7b7cfffbf9d9b12fccd&camp=1634&creative=6738

k4ujOMz-x6o.title: Introducing Oxford Reading Buddy: A new digital reading service
k4ujOMz-x6o.description:
Oxford Reading Buddy is a digital reading service that supports each child's personal reading journey, motivates them to succeed, and provides teachers with valuable insights into their attainment and development. It is an easy to use and fully optimised digital platform that can be embedded into literacy lessons in order to seamlessly support independent reading.

- Coaching eBooks that are accompanied by a personalised ‘Reading Buddy’ who models key comprehension strategies, supporting children as they read

- An extensive eBook library, with hundreds of eBooks from loved and trusted Oxford series such as Oxford Reading Tree, Treetops, and Project X, providing children with extra practice and consolidating their learning

- Quizzes that are carefully matched to each eBook, as well as further quizzes for Oxford’s print books that teachers may already in their schools, deepening and developing children’s comprehension skills

- Progression for every child that is underpinned by the expertly devised Oxford Levels system, ensuring every child is reading at the appropriate level for their needs

- Detailed progress reports and data to support teachers with insights into each child’s attainment and reading development, so they can quickly pinpoint where extra support is needed

- An in-built reward system, where children gain badges as they progress in their reading, building motivation into every step of their reading journey

Find out more at www.oxfordprimary.co.uk/readingbuddy

VMpu9gVcT5g.title: The Concrete-Pictorial-Abstract approach
VMpu9gVcT5g.description:
Professor Berinderjeet Kaur introduces the concrete-pictorial-abstract (CPA) approach to teaching Maths. She discusses the benefits of this approach to achieve Mastery, and how teachers can implement it in the classroom. 

Oxford Secondary have worked closely with Singapore Mastery experts to create a UK KS3 version of their most popular series, ‘Discovering Mathematics’. During a visit to the UK, we took the opportunity to sit down with the Singapore Consultant for the series, Professor Berinderjeet Kaur, Professor of Mathematics Education at the National Institute of Education in Singapore.

vsY6OqZsFUs.title: Your questions answered by a Read Write Inc. Phonics Model School
vsY6OqZsFUs.description:
Read Write Inc. Model Schools demonstrate best practice teaching literacy using the Read Write Inc. Phonics programme. They have transformed their literacy teaching by using Read Write Inc. Phonics, a reading and writing programme created by Ruth Miskin. It draws upon experience gained in more than 4000 schools over 10 years and is published by Oxford University Press.

The Model Schools are keen for teachers from local schools to watch lessons and see first-hand the impact Read Write Inc. Phonics has on results, behaviour and children’s engagement. There are 61 Model Schools across the UK. varying in size and demographic. 

In this video one of the Model Schools, Broadford Primary School, answer the commonly asked questions they are asked as a Read Write Inc. Model School. 

Find a Read Write Inc. Model School near you: www.oxfordprimary.co.uk/rwimodelschools

1IFEuzMP4qg.title: Make your own Goozillas slime!
1IFEuzMP4qg.description:
What you'll need:

• A mixing bowl and a spoon
• 250ml PVA glue
• 2 TBSP Bicarbonate of soda
• Green food colouring
• 3 TBSP Contact lens solution

Method:
1. Mix the glue and bicarbonate of soda.
2. Add the green food colouring and contact lens solution and mix thoroughly until the slime begins to form.
3. Knead your slime until it becomes super smooth and stretchy (if it’s too sticky add a little more contact lens solution).
4. It’s slime time!

They’re gooey, green, and completely slime-tastic, meet the Goozillas! Do you dare to enter the World of Slime and play all the levels in a quest to save the Goozillas from destruction? 

Find out more about this exciting series of illustrated young fiction books for children aged 5+: http://ow.ly/KYN730g9cZ1

5y9NjaDz214.title: Webinar: Considering Comprehension Across English AND Maths
5y9NjaDz214.description:
Reading Comprehension and Mathematical Reasoning are essentially the same thing. So why is the language surrounding them so different, not to mention the strategies for teaching them? 

Join NAHT Edge Director James Bowen and Primary Professional Development Leaders, Nicola Romaine and Louise Pennington, who will will be exploring just how this cross-curricular skill could be married up between subject leaders, what this might look like and what areas subject leaders can focus on to do this.

DRTfENz_yG4.title: Panel Discussion with Michael Morpurgo, Lauren Child, Prof. Kim Reynolds, Nikki Gamble & David Reedy
DRTfENz_yG4.description:
‘For the Love of Reading: Passing on the Passion’ was a Primary English Conference from Oxford University Press, that explored how we can pass on our own passion for reading and stories onto the next generation – and why it is so vital that we do so. 

David Reedy, Generael Secretary for the United Kingdom Literacy Association (UKLA), leads a fascinating panel discussion with Michael Morpurgo, Lauren Child, Professor Kim Reynolds and Nikki Gamble, exploring some of the UKLA's recommendations for nurturing a love of reading in the next generations.

Browse our selection of free resources and videos from the day by registering free on Oxford Owl: https://www.oxfordowl.co.uk/direct-link/love-reading

WUOInr6fKAk.title: Daisy Christodoulou - Making Good Progress?
WUOInr6fKAk.description:
Daisy Christodoulou discusses her research and motivation for writing ‘Making Good Progress? The future of Assessment for Learning’. 

Daisy Christodoulou is the Head of Assessment at Ark Schools, a network of 35 academy schools in the UK. She works on assessment reform, replacements for UK National Curriculum levels and readiness for new national exams. She has taught in two London comprehensives and has been part of UK government commissions on the future of teacher training and assessment.

Find out more about ‘Making Good Progress?’ and our full range of practical, professional books for Primary and Secondary school teachers: www.oup.com/education/teaching

bJXJEgi-aPQ.title: Panel Discussion with Michael Morpurgo, Lauren Child, Prof. Kim Reynolds, Nikki Gamble & David Reedy
bJXJEgi-aPQ.description:
‘For the Love of Reading: Passing on the Passion’ was a Primary English Conference from Oxford University Press, that explored how we can pass on our own passion for reading and stories onto the next generation – and why it is so vital that we do so. 

David Reedy, Generael Secretary for the United Kingdom Literacy Association (UKLA), leads a fascinating panel discussion with Michael Morpurgo, Lauren Child, Professor Kim Reynolds and Nikki Gamble, exploring some of the UKLA's recommendations for nurturing a love of reading in the next generations.

Browse our selection of free resources and videos from the day by registering free on Oxford Owl: https://www.oxfordowl.co.uk/direct-link/love-reading

ZB_NKyxuCyg.title: Running Successful Book Groups - Nikki Gamble (Session)
ZB_NKyxuCyg.description:
‘For the Love of Reading: Passing on the Passion’ was a Primary English Conference from Oxford University Press, that explored how we can pass on our own passion for reading and stories onto the next generation – and why it is so vital that we do so. 

In this participative seminar, Nikki Gamble explores how to cultivate book groups as a vehicle for developing reading for pleasure and raise reading attainment.

Browse our selection of free resources and videos from the day by registering free on Oxford Owl: https://www.oxfordowl.co.uk/direct-link/love-reading

5wRItaVuChM.title: Why Teacher Development is the Growing Priority - David Weston (Keynote)
5wRItaVuChM.description:
‘Developing Great Teaching’ was a professional development conference from Oxford University Press. It drew on the findings of the Teacher Development Trust’s review into effective professional development (‘Developing Great Teaching’, 2015), and created a forum to consider which models and approaches lead to sustained school improvement. It was held jointly with the Teacher Development Trust and the National Association of Head Teachers. 

In this conference keynote, TDT Chief Executive David Weston sets out the key policy and research reasons that are encouraging school leaders to prioritise a new approach to professional development.

Browse our selection of free resources and videos from the day by registering free on Oxford Owl:  
https://www.oxfordowl.co.uk/direct-link/great-teaching-london

We filmed a number of the sessions to help you share learning from the day back at school. Further videos providing a summary of key points from the presentations are available from www.oup.com/education/researchED

This excerpt is taken from Helen Rogerson’s session ‘How does a regular classroom teacher engage with research?’
Helen Rogerson has been a science teacher for 13 years, and a head of department for five of those. Alongside teaching, Helen is a member of the TES Science teacher panel and Chair of the Association of Science Education West of England Regional Committee.

This excerpt is taken from Jack Marwood’s session ’10 things you should know about primary maths’

Jack Marwood is a primary school teacher and education writer. He has contributed to the Times Educational Supplement, Schools Week and the Guardian. He also speaks about education, and has appeared at the Battle of Ideas and the Festival of Education. His writing questions many of the assumptions made about education, and he is a firm advocate of using evidence to justify opinions.

Stephen Holmes is a Research Fellow at Ofqual where he has worked since May 2013. He has been lead researcher on a number of projects, particularly relating to maths and science GCSEs. We were delighted to welcome over 300 teachers and 40 guest speakers to the University of Oxford’s Mathematical Institute for the very first researchED Maths and Science conference.

This excerpt is taken from Mark McCourt’s session ‘Teaching for mastery: what it is, what it isn’t and why you are being lied to’
Mark McCourt is a leading figure in mathematics education. He was a Director at the National Centre for Excellence in the Teaching of Mathematics (NCETM) and has also been a school leader, an Advanced Skills Teacher, a school inspector and a teacher trainer. Mark founded and was Chairman of the Teacher Development Trust. He has extensive experience of mathematics teaching and learning across all age and ability groups, having taught students from age 3 to PhD.

Mary Whitehouse co-directs both the York Science Project and the Twenty First Century Science Project and is a member of the University of York Science Education Group. http://www.oxfordprimary.co.uk/greatteachingcardiff

The New Deal will support and enable all teachers and practitioners to get the professional development they need to improve their students’ learning, and stipulates that this PD provision must be of the highest quality and founded on the latest research evidence.   

A collaboration between Oxford University Press, the Teacher Development Trust, NAHT and NAHT Edge, this conference created a forum to share understanding of exactly what this means and what it should look like for practitioners across Wales.

9GGQf3Tksxc.title: Spell with Pip - a game to help children practise spelling
9GGQf3Tksxc.description:
*Please note - Spell with Pip is being discontinued and will be removed from the iTunes and Android app stores in August 2017. Users that have already purchased the app will be able to continue to use it but without future support or updates.*

Help children aged 4--8 practise their spelling with Spell with Pip. This interactive, entertaining and engaging spelling game is so much fun children won't even know they are practising their spelling! 

The app focuses on words that children commonly find hard to spell, based on the latest research from the team behind the world-famous, market-leading Oxford Dictionaries for children.

Suitable for users and learners of either US or UK English.

TcArwuOmtjA.description:
The River Singers follows four young water voles on an epic journey along the Great River. With dangers lurking at every turn, will they ever find a safe place to call home?

Written by ecologist and Oxford academic Tom Moorhouse, The River Singers will be loved by children who are interested in the natural world, and any child who loves a good adventure! The book is filled with wonderful illustrations by Simon Mendez.

CObOpd0ydH4.title: Meet the creators of Oliver and the Seawigs
CObOpd0ydH4.description:
Get ready Oliver and the Seawigs, an unforgettable, hilarious, gorgeously illustrated children's adventure story from two of the most inspirational talents in children's books, Philip Reeve and Sarah McIntyre. 

Along with his new friends—a grumpy old albatross, a short-sighted mermaid, and a friendly island called Cliff, Oliver goes off in search of his missing parents. But before he can put his rescue plan into action there's the evil Stacey de Lacey and an army of pesky sea monkeys to contend with... 

Find out more: http://ukcatalogue.oup.com/product/9780192734556.do

GKjB7YZ6m8E.title: Project X CODE - impact in schools
GKjB7YZ6m8E.description:
A breakthrough for special needs and struggling readers, Project X CODE is the only reading intervention to embed systematic synthetic phonics within a highly motivational adventure series.  To get the most of the intervention in the classroom, the resources are now complemented with specialist Project X CODE training provided by Edge Hill University. 

To find out how Project X CODE can make a difference in your school, visit http://www.oup.com/oxed/primary/projectx/code/  To find out about the Project X CODE training, go to https://readingsupport.edgehill.ac.uk
